 the biblical and talmudic eras most gentiles were assumed to be idolators. In the Middle Ages most rabbis considered their Christian neighbors idolators, and Christian enmity sharpened the otherness Jews felt toward their Christian hosts. Muslims were monotheists, but Jewish-Muslim relations were sometimes positive and at other times difficult. With the advent secular tolerance in modernity, Jews found themselves in a new relationship with their gentile neighbors. How should Jews relate to gentiles today, and what are the bounds of Jewish tolerance and religious pluralism? The book will interest both Jewish laypersons familiar with Jewish tradition as well as scholars of theology and interfaith relations  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aGentiles in rabbinical literature. 0aGentiles in the Bible. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 0aRabbinical literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aAfterlife.  aBiblical covenant.  aChristian theology of Jews and Judaism.  aIdolatry.  aInterfaith.  aJewish law.  aJewish theology.  aJewish-Christian relations.  aPluralism.  aTolerance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2z978311117804208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023z97831113